data.message: Hello TSP members! Many thanks to those of you who have done our first follow-up survey sent out two weeks ago. For those of you who haven't, don't forget to check your email and complete it for a $20 gift card! You’ll earn an additional $20 at the end if you fill out all surveys!

Just a friendly reminder to check your email and fill out the first follow-up survey that we sent out last week. Remember, you'll receive $20 for completing it and will receive an additional $20 at the end if you complete all follow-up surveys!
Just finished it, sorry!
No problem, 10397! Thank you for participating! :D
Thank you ! :)

Hello TSP members! Yesterday’s post concludes our 90-day program. Please check your email this week for our first follow-up survey. You will receive a $20 gift card upon completion.We hope that our Facebook group has been enjoyable, educational, and life-changing in some way, whether it be a shift in your perspective towards smoking, or a commitment towards a healthier, smoke-free life. All of us at TSP have enjoyed reading your comments and interacting with you online, and we truly thank you for your participation.Although we will no longer be posting daily, you are welcome to remain in this secret group and access all of the content we've shared over the past 90 days. Furthermore, we're still available to answer any questions/concerns about smoking, and we're open to any feedback/suggestions you may have for our program.Again, from all of us at TSP, thank you and good luck in your future endeavors!

#90: Times they are a-changin’. Instead of endorsing smoking, Hollywood stars are now starting a new trend and quitting for their health. Check out this slideshow of all the actors and celebrities who have recently taken the dive and quit smoking! What do you think of this trend? #socialreflection
data.name: 10 Celebrities Who Quit Smoking
data.caption: www.shape.com
data.description: Cold turkey, hypnotism, electronic cessation...find out how 10 celebs kicked their smoking habit for good.

data.message: It's good that we have celebrities who are willing to shed light on their quitting and give a good example to kids and teens, but it wouldn't really affect adults. Also, a lot of times you don't know that celebrities smoke.
It's good for them but the influence to smoke is there still
#89: Does hearing that rat poison is found in cigarettes change the way you feel about smoking? #beingconscious
Not really, it's like telling people what hot dogs are made from. Yeah, we know it's not good but it doesn't really change anything.
No I've known for a long time that they contained dangerous chemicals
No, I've known that. Ammonia too.

#88: Your risk for stroke is now the same as a person who never smoked, your risk of lung cancer has dropped to half that of a continual smoker, and your risk of coronary disease and death in general have returned to nearly the level of people who have never smoked before. How do you feel knowing that you’re not doomed to have cancer? #beingconscious
I feel pretty much the same
It'd be nice, sure. But I'm still currently ambiguous so it probably won't happen immediately.
Well considering we all still smoke, none of know howbot feels, but I'm sure it would be pretty nice
#87: Have you noticed more and more celebrities quitting smoking? Do you think this encourages more people to say goodbye to cigarettes? #socialreflection
I think it might help to encourage some people, but not a lot.
I never really notice celebrities who smoke or not
It will definitely give young people who look up to these celebrities a small incentive to quit. But a lot of times it's not publicized who smokes and who doesn't.

#86: As a result of the 2009 Family Smoking Prevention and Tobacco Control Act, tobacco companies have been banned from offering free samples and selling cigarettes in packages that contain fewer than 20 cigarettes. Why do you think that is? #beingconscious

There's a million places to buy just one cigarette at a time. There's also places that don't id and really don't care because it's money. But you can't give free samples out on the street probably because there'd be no way to id those who take them.
With the 90 days being almost over I am curious to hear about your experience: What is the most important thing you have learned from TSP? #TDII
#85: Have you ever heard this statistic before? How many smokers do you know? Divide that number by three and that’s how many may die in the future from a smoking-related illness. #beingconscious
I've never heard that actually. I've heard one in five.
Nope, never heard that statistic but sounds pretty reasonable

#84: Flavored cigarettes have been outlawed for years now, yet e-cig companies are using old tricks to gain new customers while they still can. Would you have been more likely to start smoking as a minor if the product you used was flavored like your favorite candy? #ecig
Obviously, seeing how I started smoking young as it is, flavored cigarettes would have made it that much easier to start.
Probably not more likely but I would have paid more for flavored. There used to be a camel pink flavor that tasted like candy when I first started and it got shut down.
More than likely not because I don't like the candy flavors all that well

data.message: #83: In movies and TV shows, smoking used to be a popular prop to make characters seem more edgy or cool. Researchers and even some members of Congress are urging Hollywood to cut out smoking images targeting youth. Do you think smoking in movies should mean they get a R-rating? Why? #beingconscious
No because no matter what the youth will always have something else influencing them to smoke
I don't think it should receive an R rating just for having someone smoking in it, but then again I don't think there should be smoking in anything with less than an R rating so...

#82: One year after a cigarette, the additional risk of coronary heart disease accumulated while smoking has decreased by half. AND the health of your gums and teeth have improved drastically. What other changes in your life would be present after not smoking for 365 days? #beingconscious
Lungs are somewhat stronger
Stronger lungs, some claim a better sense of taste and smell.
You can breath better, sleep better; better sense of taste and smell.

#81: As far back as 1969, tobacco companies have said they have “taken a great many steps to avoid advertising directed to young people”, but 10 years later, they arranged for their cigarettes to be featured in The Muppet Movie. What do you think about tobacco companies targeting young people through the media? #beingconscious
According to the description that was 1979. Well before our time. Laws and stigma were very different back then. That same action would not be tolerated in this day and age.
I think it is wrong because young people are easily manipulated, also I think if you've started at a really young age it is harder to quit.

#80: It’s true, all the new tobacco legislation sure is making it harder to smoke. But have you ever turned it on its head? How is this new legislation making it easier for you to quit? What new laws or regulations would be really helpful to you if you decided to stop smoking? #socialreflection
I honestly have no idea
Well, you're not allowed to smoke in most public buildings so you don't have to walk into a place like a restaurant with people smoking, so it doesn't give you the urge to smoke, plus you can't so...

It doesn't. Regarding the newest legislation, I dont have any children under 18 either born to me or in my household so it really doesn't affect me. And any other legislation we've basically grown up with so we've never had to really change.
#79: Coughing, sinus congestion, fatigue, and shortness of breath all decrease after this long without a cigarette. What can you do with a clear airway that you can’t do now? #beingconscious

Have a much more active lifestyle. I lived in Denver Colorado for a few months last year and I absolutely loved going and climbing in the mountains, but it definitely kicked my ass being that I've smoked for about 8 years now.
Stairs. Lots and lots of stairs for exercise.
#78: Why might your smoking buddies want you to keep smoking? What are their motives? #socialreflection
So if they ain't got no smokes they can bum off me
Because if I didn't smoke I probably wouldn't be around them as much
I know stopping smoking is not easy. How confident are you that you could quit smoking if you tried? #TDII

#77: Anyone who smokes knows someone who wants them to quit. Think about the people in your life who want you to quit: why do they want this so badly for you? What types of arguments do they have? #socialreflection
My mom for my health.
Mostly they want me to stop for my own health

data.message: #76: Every year it seems like there’s a new bill or law passed that’s tightening up the smoking legislation. What recent changes to tobacco laws in your community are making it harder for you to smoke? Do you think these new laws protect more people than they inconvenience? #socialreflection
I usually smoke anyways

#75: FACT: Treatments cost between $3-$10/day, and some health insurances cover medications and/or counseling. Would you spend a little more money to finally stop throwing cash down that bottomless cigarette-pit? Why do you think so many smokers don’t? #beingconscious
Half the time it don't work

"Treatments" are like diets. There's a million of them and no treatment works on the same on any two people. By the time you find the one that works for you, you've spent a good chunk of money, on top of the money youre spending on cigarettes because the treatments don't work and you're still smoking.
#74: When you're online, how is smoking portrayed on your favorite sites such as Facebook or YouTube? What messages are being sent online about smoking? #socialreflection
I never pay attention if there are any ads
#73: Have you noticed how smoking is portrayed in magazines and advertisements? How do you feel about the way it's represented to the world? #socialreflection
I never really pay much attention
#72: Lots of people are bothered by the strong smell of nail polish remover, but did you know that anyone who smokes a cigarette is inhaling this chemical into their lungs? #beingconscious
Yea I knew this
#71: How is smoking portrayed on TV? What have you noticed about characters who smoke on TV shows or in movies? #socialreflection
#70: Check out what Big Tobacco companies consider their 'Doomsday Scenario'. What do you think about what their records say? #socialreflection

Every company has a scenario like this. A worst case scenario, if you will. And it always has something to do with how the business would lose its momentum and profit. A generation that does not smoke is the death of Big Tobacco. This is reasonable.

Did you know that you can avoid almost all of the negative long-term health consequences of smoking if you quit before you are 30 years old? Does that change how you feel about smoking and quitting? #TDII
I've got to run guys - check out this study if you're interested http://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/NEJMsa1211128
Also check out these benefits of quitting:

#69: Check out this link to view which U.S. College Campuses and Universities have 100% Smoke-Free ordinances. Do you think it’s a good idea to make institutions of higher education smoke free? #socialreflection http://buff.ly/1ihS4qX
data.name: pdf/smokefreecollegesuniversities.pdf
data.caption: no-smoke.org

data.message: No, I think it should be someone's choice to be able to smoke where they want, although the same courtesy should be shown to non-smokers as well.

Yes and no. They should have designated smoking areas. I typically ignore no smoking rules if I'm in a spot secluded or if other smokers are there too. I pay to be on this campus, administration gets paid to be here. The students, with discretion, decide which areas are smoking areas.
If someone wanna smoke they will no matter what

data.message: #68: Many people don’t like to label themselves as a “smoker”. The fact remains that switching to an e-cig does not mean you’ve stopped ingesting addictive and harmful chemicals. And Big Tobacco would much rather you switch and remain a loyal customer, than deciding to quit once and for all. Have you ever felt like you had to hide your smoking? #ecig
This was already a question posted before, I believe. I said no then, and I'm saying no now.
Not since I was a minor
Havent posted an update in a while. Still smoking unfortunately. Cut down dramatically, only about 4 a day.

#67: Your overall blood circulation has improved, walking has become easier, and your lung function has increased significantly. Have you noticed anything physical becoming more difficult as you smoke more? #beingconscious
No I usually walk about 5 miles a day easily while smoking
The only thing that happens when I smoke a lot is a little chest congestion, but it doesn't really affect my breathing.
I used to bike 20+ miles a day smoking whenever I wanted one.

#66: Check out this link to see what the Tobacco Control Laws are like in your state. Be sure to know the smoking legislation if you plan on traveling. What do you think about the laws in your state? #socialreflection

data.message: This link doesn't work on any of my devices.
#65: Have you noticed your sense of smell being impacted by your smoking? What different kinds of scents have you missed since you started smoking? #beingconscious
I've never noticed my sense of smell failing. I usually smell things before anyone else.
I've smoked since I was little so I've never noticed a difference in my sense of smell.
I've never had a good sense of smell
Quitting smoking may not be number one on your current priorities list. What would make quitting more important to you? #TDII

#64: Why do you think romantic partners have such a big impact on how much you smoke? If you’re in a relationship, what could your partner do to help you change your ways, and if not, would you be willing to quit smoking to begin a new relationship? #beingconscious
My fiance doesn't smoke, but he's a part of the reason why I cut down a lot. We're building a life together and smoking is not something we really should spend money on.

I've been single for a long time and I would really like to find someone I like that doesn't smoke because I would like to quit and if I was with someone who didn't smoke it would help me to quit soo much!
Most people I date are smokers too

#61: Since President Obama signed the Family Smoking Prevention and Tobacco Control Act into law, tobacco companies have been banned from brand sponsorship of sports and entertainment events. Do you think the fans at these events will miss their favorite Tobacco brands at their game or show? #socialreflection
I don't think so. Games should be enjoyed for the sport and teams not the advertisement banners

Highly unlikely. It's very unlikely that anyone will even remember the advertisements from the event. Advertisements at these sorts of events are almost entirely psychological. such as Sprite at a basketball game. When you eventually get thirsty, Sprite is likely to be the last beverage you saw and in turn will up the chance that you will order a Sprite.
Thanks for sharing your views!

#59: FACT: Research shows that although some people quit cold turkey successfully, the most effective way to quit smoking is using a combo of counseling plus nicotine replacement therapy (NRT’s, like patch or gum) or medicine (like bupropion SR). What have you heard about NRT’s? Would you consider using them? #beingconscious

I don't see how counseling helps except maybe for stress management. Also, I take Bupropion SR. It's one generic form of Welbutrin. Never helped me quit or made me want to smoke less.As for NRTs, when you use them you are simply breaking the hand to mouth habit, not the nicotine habit.
Thank you for sharing!
#63: What would you do with those 18 days -- go on a trip? Stay home and finally watch that movie everyone’s been talking about? #beingconscious
I'm not sure
I would use it to help spread out all of the things I already don't have time for in my life.

data.message: #62: On average, smokers get sick more often than nonsmokers. How would work or school be different if you didn’t smoke? #beingconscious

I actually don't get sick more than once a year. Twice if I'm really stressed out during cold and flu season. And even then I love by the mantra "pop a pill and go." If someone in my house is sick I take extra immune boosters. I dont have time to get sick and its really easy not to get sick.
I usually hardly get sick
#60: Who in your life would benefit if you decided to quit smoking? Think of all the people your smoking touches and comment on each other’s lists. #smokingaffectsall
My fiance mainly. He is around it the most
Probably my daughter when she is old enough to understand

#58: Because your nerve endings have started to re-grow, your ability to smell and taste is enhanced. How much better does everything taste when you don’t smoke? Do you miss any of your favorite dishes? #beingconscious
Things taste better when I haven't smoked in a while, definitely. I don't miss anything though
Everything tastes about the same to me
#57: How do you think your life would change if you always smelled fresh and never like a cigarette? #balance
I don't really know how my life would be different
My life wouldnt be different. If I have an interview or the like I dont smoke beforehand.
How would you support a friend who wants to quit smoking? #TDII

#54: Quitting smoking can slow balding in men. Fellas, does this seem like a good reason to think about quitting? And ladies, how would this fact help you encourage your male loved ones to quit smoking?  #beingconscious
I'm not really afraid of losing my hair honestly
This is a really shallow question. I love my fiance regardless.
Thanks for sharing your thoughts!

#52: Ever wondered how much $ you’ve spent on smoking so far? Use this smoking calculator and find out once and for all. Tell us what your number is and what you’d spend that on if you could get it back. #beingconscious
data.name: Cost Savings Calculator

data.message: I spend roughly $135 a month on cigarettes. I'd probably put it toward student loans and debt.
I spend roughly $120 a month. I'd use it for my daughter
Thanks for trying the calculator! :)
#51: Why do you think hookah has held on to a "cool" reputation even though it's just as unhealthy as other forms of tobacco use? #beingconscious
It's because of the flavors you can get. I personally don't like hookah unless it's got green in it
Because of the flavors and the social scene it belongs to. You don't smoke hookah alone.
Great points. Thanks for sharing!

#55: Hey ladies, did you know that quitting smoking can reduce the chances of ectopic pregnancy, miscarriage, still birth, and having a low birth weight baby? What do you think about this? Guys, how does knowing this make you feel about encouraging the women you love to quit smoking? #beingconscious
If a woman is pregnant by me she ain't smoking

#53: While ammonia helps keep our bathrooms and kitchens clean, it does anything but that for our lungs. Does learning it's found in cigarettes change the way you think or feel about smoking? #beingconscious
Not particularly. There's like over seven thousand chemicals in cigarettes I believe? I'm certainly not surprised that they're harmful.
How does your smoking affect your loved ones, kids, or significant other? What do they think about your smoking? #TDII

#50: FACT: People usually take two or three attempts to successfully quit for good. Aaliyah said it best: If at first you don't succeed, Dust yourself off and try again. Would you be able to try again? #beingconscious
Yes I know I can eventually
Of course I'd be able to try again.

#49: Everyone wants to know whether electronic cigarettes can help smokers quit. Unfortunately, studies are showing that they are not any more effective than a placebo. So health professionals still recommend using well-studied strategies like counseling or Nicotine Replacement Therapy (patch, gum) when you’re ready to quit. #ecig
I don't think any of it works
I don't think I understand how counseling works for smoking. Stress control? Either way, any sort of nicotine coming into your body will not help you quit.

data.name: Electronic Cigarettes (e-Cigarettes)
data.caption: www.fda.gov
data.description: Electronic cigarettes, also known as e-cigarettes, are battery-operated products designed to deliver nicotine, flavor and other chemicals. They turn chemicals, including highly addictive nicotine, into...

data.message: I've tried them they don't work the same for me. But i can see where minors could be convinced they healthier

If I was still a minor, I wouldnt be concerned if they were healthier. I started smoking at thirteen. The only thing I was ever worried about was my mom finding my pack and smelling it on me. E-cigs don't smell and they're so much easier to hide. Minors aren't worried about their health.

#47: Your chance of a heart attack has already decreased after only one day without a cigarette. Your body will thank you. What do you usually think of when considering being smoke free for a full day? #beingconscious
I usually end up getting stressed so never can be cigarette free
Nothing. I do it all the time when I spend the day with my parents. I'm about to do it today, actually.
#46: Have you heard any conflicting information about smokeless tobacco? How do you feel now knowing the truth? #beingconscious
I don't really use smokeless tobacco. I haven't heard of any conflicts with it
I don't know anything about smokeless tobacco other than I'd never date a man that chews and that chewing/dip can cause all kinds of mouth cancer.

#45: Another part of the Family Smoking Prevention and Tobacco Control Act (signed into law by President Obama in '09) prevents tobacco companies from making health claims about any supposed “reduced risk” of any of their products that might encourage new smokers or discourage smokers from quitting. Do you think this is fair? #socialreflection
Yea it makes sense.

Yes and no. Smoking is terrible for your health, it affects three major organ systems just off the top of my head. Prevention is key, and having strict guidelines for advertising is a big help. However, smoking doesn't kill; the diseases it causes do. There are mild carcinogens in just about everything at this point, from plastic to processed food, and while you hear about them in wild articles on Facebook that don't quite have all the facts right, they aren't widely known, and they should be talked about and advertised about just as much as tobacco products.

#44: What’s your take on Big Tobacco? Do you defend tobacco companies, or do you side with those who are critical of Big Tobacco? What types of things have you heard about tobacco companies? #beingconscious
I don't defend them or go against them. I know smoking is not healthy for me but it's my choice. Not the companies fault

I second what 10430 said. To put it bluntly, I'm a twenty something year old woman who takes responsibility for her choices and actions. I'm in College, and I have bills to pay. I don't care about Big Tobacco currently. They're the least of my concerns.
What would you miss most if you quit smoking for good? #TDII
I've got to run guys. Check out this table with pros and cons for smoking and quitting. See you next week.
Nothing lol

#43: There are lots of Nicotine Replacement Therapies, or NRT’s, available over-the-counter: the patch, gum, lozenge, nasal spray, and inhaler. What have you heard about NRT’s? Would you ever consider trying them? #beingconscious
I've tried a couple of them but none has ever worked for me
Tried gum and it tasted like pepper. Vaping helped a lot.
I've heard that they're good to get off smoking, but I'd rather quit than use a substitute.

#42: What do you think middle school and high school nonsmokers are more likely to pick up: a cigarette, which they know are bad, smelly, and frowned upon, or a shiny, gadget-y, trend setting e-cig? Read this article to find out more about how under-aged kids are responding to the new e-cigs craze. #ecig http://buff.ly/1hyGt7l
They go for the ecigg because it's "safer" then ciggs. Plus they want to fit in
I think it really depends on what the friend group has and also how much money they have access to. A good vape set up runs about eighty to a hundred bucks where I live.
Thanks for sharing your thoughts!

#37: Children of smokers are far more likely to start smoking than children of nonsmokers and children of ex-smokers. Were you brought up in a home where smoking was allowed? If so, how do you think this affected your decision to start smoking? If not, where do you think your attitudes about smoking originated? #beingconscious
My grandparents didn't smoke but my step dad did and i used to finish off his when he'd flick them into the yard
My uncle smoked, but rarely ever around me or my siblings, and my mother stopped smoking after she had my sister, so I was never really around it.

My parents quit when we were really little to give us the best chance of not ever smoking. My brother doesn't smoke. My attitudes mostly came from my childhood best friend's house down the block where her mom, who was a single mother, smoked. We got the opportunity to smoke when her mom was at work and we walked home from school together.
Thank you for sharing.
#35: Tell us how you get rid of the smoky smell after a cigarette. #balance
I never worry about it because everyone will know eventually that  I smoke

I Febreeze things that don't get washed everyday, like winter jackets and hoodies, and I change clothes if I have somewhere important to go later in the day. If I'm going somewhere where it matters if I smell badly of smoke, like a job interview, I just don't smoke until after it's over.
Never really cared honestly.
Thanks for sharing!

data.message: #41: A Dartmouth Medical study reported that adolescents who viewed smoking in movies were more than 50% more likely to smoke than those who didn’t watch smoking in movies. What do you think the younger generation is learning about tobacco and cigarettes? #beingconscious
I do not think tv shows and movies influence kids to smoke

#40: The carbon monoxide level in your blood drops down as the oxygen level in your blood increases back to normal. Have you ever noticed a difference in your breathing when you’ve been without a cigarette for 12 hours? #beingconscious

It depends on the day. Some days, (not very often but it happens) I wake up and I wheeze like I've been smoking for thirty years. Or some days my breathing is very shallow and weird, like I can't take a deep breath until I smoke a cigarette. But most days when I wake up, I feel great.
Not really no I don't notice a difference

#39: FACT:  Just like with any other addiction, quitting can be difficult, and it might be hard to do it alone. Would you be able to get the support you need if you wanted to quit smoking? What would you try? #beingconscious
I'd have support from my friends but not my family

#38: In 2009, President Obama signed into law the Family Smoking Prevention and Tobacco Control Act. Part of this law bans all cigarettes that contain a characterizing flavor, including all fruit and candy flavors. Do you think it's a good thing to ban candy and fruit-flavored cigarettes? Who do you think this portion of the law is trying to protect? #socialreflection
I don't think it's right to ban good tasting cigarettes. Kids are going to do what they want anyways

#36: Social situations can make it hard not to smoke, especially when alcohol is involved. Does alcohol affect your smoking? How would you change that if you wanted to cut down or quit? #beingconscious
I usually tend to smoke more when i drink
Alcohol makes me want to smoke more, definitely. If I wanted to quit I would either abstain or make sure I didn't have any cigarettes at all.
Definitely makes me want to smoke, but I could just as easily switch it to gum chewing or eating bar nuts.
In today's post we asked you about alcohol and smoking. Why do you think the two go together for so many people? #TDII

#34: If you quit smoking, the amount of secondhand smoke present in your home will decrease immediately, keeping your pets safe. Post a pic of your pet if you have one. How much did you think about nearby animals when you lit up before? #smokingaffectsall

My cat is my life. Her name is Alice, she's a Norwegian Forest Cat, so she's huge. About the size of a medium sized dog. I always think about animals when I smoke in a place that has them, and I don't smoke in the same room as them. Their sense of smell is so much greater than ours, so I imagine it kills them to smell the smoke.
I'm so happy we don't smoke in our house! We have kids, a cat, and a snake! They don't deserve to breathe in second hand smoke
My armadillo lizard Dagon. I do not smoke in the house so he is not exposed to second hand smoke.
Never really thought about pets, will definitely remember that from now on.

data.message: #33: Being labeled as “the smoker” can be tough. Have you ever felt uncomfortable around people who don’t smoke? #balance
On occasion cause around them I sometimes feel as if they look down on me
Nah. If they don't wanna be around my smoke, they can go do something for 10 minutes while I take a smoke break lol

It's not hard to find people who smoke at universities. That's how I make a lot of my friends, but I don't smoke around people who don't simply out of respect, so unless I say something about it, a lot of times they don't even know I do.

#29: It’s true, we all know quitting smoking is hard. But switching to another, more socially-acceptable way of ingesting nicotine won’t help you conquer your addiction. What would you rather do, take the easy way and switch to e-cigs, staying addicted and making these e-cig companies more money, or quit once and for all to live free of any level of nicotine-addiction? How would you “enjoy your life more”? #ecig
I'd rather quit because the e cigarettes don't work for me

Ecigs don't work. Plus my dr. Straight up told me (when I decided to try to quit once) that if I absolutely had to smoke, she'd rather me smoke a real one rather than an ecig. She didn't like how much it increases your chance for pneumonia by putting fluid directly into your lungs
I'd rather quit. If you're going to quit, you might as well go all the way.
Thanks for sharing your views!

#32: Children can’t really distinguish between vapor and smoke. What they do see is important adults in their life setting an example for how to take care of themselves, what they spend their money on, and their attitudes about addictive substances. Would you hide your e-cig smoking from a child? #ecig
With proper education, children shouldn't want to try it. But that's just something parents need to do with their kids.
I wouldn't smoke anything in front of my kids. "Do as I say, not as I do" doesn't work for kids anymore. I'll quit before I have kids anyway.

#31: Quitting smoking can help preserve our planet! Without cigarette smoke, the chances of household fires decrease and less secondhand smoke is added into the air we breathe. Can you think of any other environmental improvements that might result from less smoke? #beingconscious
Not really. As long as you're responsible about smoking you're fine. You'd have to cut out bbqing and campfires too before you even started an argument about cigarettes lol
I'm sure the chemicals in the smoke are not healthy for the ozone.
The filters that people throw on the ground are not biodegradable. They're made with some sort of plastic. If less people smoked, there would be less filters on the ground.

If our government would stop regulating the harmful chemicals that US cigarette companies use, they would be much less carcinogenic than they are now. It also would probably do less damage to our ozone and environment. More so if they changed their fiber filters to REAL COTTON filters.
#30: Cats are exposed to secondhand smoke toxins through breathing in the smoke around them, AND when they groom themselves. How can we help Fifi stop smoking? #smokingaffectsall
Not smoke in the house or apartment. Just go outside
Keep fifi  indoors. It's dangerous for outdoor kitties. Also don't smoke in the house. That's gross lol and I'm a smoker. Smoking is for outside.
You should never smoke in a house where your children and your pets live. Not if you give a damn, anyway.
Do you think you will EVER be ready to quit smoking? Why? Why not? #TDII
Yes, done it before. Not afraid of quiting.
Thanks for sharing 10412 - glad to hear that you are not afraid. How important is quitting for you right now from 1 (not at all important) to 10 (very important)?
I'd say a 2. Like a whisper in the back of the mind.
So why is it a 2 and not a 1 10412?
I know one day I'll want to quit for health and quality of life, but it isn't today, if that makes sense.
Sure, makes perfect sense 10412. What would have to happen to move your motivation up to a 5 for example?

Well currently there is nothing that could change it other than myself, and a doctor telling me I have to stop smoking or I'll die in a certain time frame. If it comes to that it goes from the 2 to a 10. Until then, I'm not too worried. I highly doubt I'll get to that point before I actually quit on my own.
How confident are you that you could quit if you ever decided to try? What quit strategy would you use?
100% confident, cold turkey. As I've said before, done it many times before, can do it again if I want to.

Glad to hear that 10412 - maybe you still find some of the things we share here at TSP useful for when you decide to try it the next time! If you have any other questions, just let me know - I'm always happy to help if I can.
I'm sure eventually I will be
#28: For which reasons would your children, real or imagined, thank you most for quitting smoking? #smokingaffectsall
Probably  the smell lol
I'm about 99% sure I won't be smoking when I have kids. But for question's sake, probably the smell and my health. Kids are smart.
The smell and the fact that my health is a lil better

data.story: Johannes Thrul created an event for 2014-15 Not Ready to Quit Yet 8.
data.name: The Doctor Is In
data.caption: The Doctor Is In
data.description: I'll be doing another session Q&A this week. Looking forward to seeing you there!

data.message: #22: Do you have a family member or know someone who has been diagnosed with some form of cancer? How has their life changed? #balance

Lots of people in my family have had cancer. Most have died.  The ones that died either didn't smoke or had cancer everywhere except their lungs. You can get cancer from anything.  Don't let fear of it make your life miserable :)

My Grandfather died of lung cancer before I was old enough to notice anything wrong, and my Great Aunt had breast cancer twice before she died. She had a daughter who is in her forties that was mentally challenged, so really her only concern was Baeatė.
My uncle died of cancer before I was born
I've personally never had anyone in my immediate family that has had cancer.
Thank you for sharing.

#27: Due to the Family Smoking Prevention and Tobacco Control Act, tobacco companies have been banned from outdoor advertising within 1,000 feet of school and playgrounds. Do you approve this portion of the Act? What do you think? #socialreflection
I don't really care tbh. Kids will do it either way and it's better than them getting into heroine or something.
I approve of it because advertising near playground is a bad influence on kids

It's definitely a good idea. What there should be within 1000' are billboards and outdoor advertising on the facts of smoking and drugs, not D.A.R.E. crap. If you just tell a child not to do something, you're not giving them the ammunition they need to actually make that choice to not pick up the cigarette or the bottle or the pipe.
I honestly don't care, if parents teach their children accordingly, it shouldn't be a problem.
#26: Who in your life nags you about smoking? What are their reasons for feeling the way that they do? #smokingaffectsall
My parents, and for the obvious health reasons.
My fiances lil sister does to us both bc of the health risks
My gf. She's just worried I'll die before her. :)
My grandmother is always on ny case about smoking. Her brother died of lung cancer

#25: LADIES: Quitting smoking can reduce your risk of breast and cervical cancer. Does this seem like a good reason to think about quitting? Guys, does this seem like a reason to encourage female loved ones to quit? #beingconscious
Not really everything gives you cancer tbh.
If they wanted to quit I'd be there to help them but if not that's their choice
I mean, it's a good reason to, but I probably won't.

#24: MALE-SMOKERS: Quitting could reduce your risk for erectile dysfunction. What do you think about that? Ladies: would this fact inspire you to encourage your male loved ones to quit? #beingconscious
I didn't even know it caused it. Kinda makes me want to really quit now
No, it doesn't. Maybe if this was the fifties. ED can be caused by dozens of different things, and there are treatments for it now.
#23: Your blood rate decreases, your pulse rate drops, and the temperature of your hands and feet increases. Have you ever noticed these changes after smoking? #beingconscious
I don't check my pulse when I smoke, but my hands actually get colder when I smoke, not warmer.
I never noticed
Have you ever noticed a connection between smoking and your mood? Is there an emotional state that gets you to light up more frequently? #TDII
Definitely stress, anger, frustration, etc.
Hi 10397 - sounds like the negative emotions are your triggers. Have you ever tried any alternative strategies to cope with these? How did it go?

My university gave out stress balls my freshman year and I still have it actually in my school bag. If I can't get away for a cigarette I just use that and after a few minutes I'm calmer and I can continue with a much better attitude!
Sounds great 10397 - it can be very useful to find out that we can make it through a stressful situation with a good strategy. What else could you try that may be helpful?
I'm not really sure. I've never really found or even looked for anything else to get me by.
That's ok. Do you want some suggestions 10397?
Yes, please!

Ok, some things you could try: Keep your hands busy: Use a stress ball (which you are already doing :)), play a game on your phone, play with a Rubik’s cube, start a fun arts and crafts project. Keep your mouth busy: Use gum, hard candy, mints, chew on toothpicks, prepare healthy snacks like veggie sticks, drink plenty of water. Any of these sound useful?
I craft for my sorority almost daily, so that could really help!
Great - give it a try and tell me how it went next week if you'd like!
I have to run for today - I'll see you next week. Have a great week!
No I usually only smoke when I feel like I could use one, it's more for the pleasure aspect.

#21: FACT: Nicotine is a very addictive drug. For some, it can be as addictive as heroin or cocaine. Have you ever had someone belittle the power of your addiction? What was it like? What did they say? #beingconscious
No, I've proven to any one who matters to me that addiction isn't an issue for me.
No one had ever told me that I'm not addicted. But I'd also like to see the research on it being as addictive as heroin because I do not concur.

data.caption: The Doctor Is In
data.description: Hi everyone, the next Q&A session will be on Wednesday. See you then!

data.message: #18: Do you ever have to hide smoking? How does that affect you? #balance
I don't ever feel like I have to hide smoking but there are certain people I don't talk about it with or do it in front of our of respect. I have a pretty open family.
When I first picked it back up I kept it hidden. But now just about everyone knows I smoke.
Nope and it honestly doesn't effect me.
Thank you for sharing.
#16: Would your life be different if others’ first impression of you was not smoky? #balance

When meeting someone in a more professional setting, I will not smoke in the clothing I am meeting this person in, and I usually won't smoke at all that day until our meeting is over for that exact reason.
Honestly I'm not too sure. I'd be less frowned down upon by my grandparents
Societies norm seems to be more accepting of smokers, but probably would change.
I personally smoke and even I don't like when I can smell smoke on someone... Or if anyone's ever been around people who will shove a short in their pocket? Lol disgusting!
Thanks for sharing!
#11: We understand that stopping smoking is not easy. On a scale of 1-10, how confident are you that you COULD quit smoking if you tried? #motivation
10. Dome it before.
5 right now bc I'm not really ready to quit ...but if I was ready and fully committed I know I could do it
I'd say about a 5 I've done it before but Idk if I'm exactly ready to again yet
If I actually wanted to, about an 8.
If I was just trying probably only about 3-4, but if I HAD to I know I could
Thanks for sharing your confidence in quitting!
#7: How would you react if you found out your son or daughter smoked cigarettes? #motivation
I'd let them make their own choices at the right age.
I'd hope that she'd be able to quit. Wouldn't want her to end up developing cancer

It depends if I'm still smoking myself or not. My parents quit smoking before my brother and I realized that they smoked, to try to give us the best chance of not picking up the habit. When they found out I smoke, they were crushed and tried everything to make me quit until they gave up. Eventually I started to cut down on my own, now. So I would let them make their own decisions and hope that I raised then with enough sense to see that they don't want to drag this ball and chain around forever, either, and quit when they're ready.
I would be upset. It also depends on how old they are at the time but I'm going to make sure I talk to my kids about how smoking is not cool and bad for your health and hopefully I quit before then

I would be disappointed but I wouldn't be able to say much other than give advice based on experience because I started at a young age also, and kids learn a lot from their parents, so if I found out they were, I would have no one to blame but myself.
Thanks for your thoughts.
#6: What’s the worst thing that could happen if you don’t quit smoking? #motivation
Die even sooner than I'm probably already going to, and then I wouldn't be around for my family.
Worst thing that could happen is cancer later on in life.
My daughter picking up the habit and developing lung cancer and having to watch her suffer.
Dying from cancer
Thank you for sharing.

#20: Big Tobacco is advertising E-Cigarettes as a safer and better way to smoke, but studies have shown that they still contain toxins, even without the smoke. Why do you think so many people who smoke are ready to adopt new products even before proper research on their safety has happened? #beingconscious
Because in society if it's new it's better. People automatically assume since its a vapor it's less harmless when the e ciggs are just as addictive and possibly even more harmful

I don't know, my my Dr actually said if you're going to smoke, smoke real ones. She had a bunch of patients get pneumonia who were using ecigs and vapes. As a health care provider she doesn't encourage smoking of course, but she'd rather me have real ones or use patches or gum than the ecigs.

I tried the e-cigarette thing, and it was super nice for a few days to not smell smoke all over me, since I don't smoke in my house. But they weren't as good. Smoking does stink, and the taste is something not many like, but we'll still do it. So might as well go with the nicer smelling and tasting option if you can.
Because the propaganda around it, people have accepted it as a safe alternative thag will help you quit smoking regularly.
#19: Can you relate to your best smoking buddy on anything other than smoking? #smokingaffectsall
Everything!  My smoking buddy and I hang out all the time outside of work. Lol we live in the same complex, work together, shop together.. lol
My smoking buddy is my best friend. And we'd still be best friends if one of us didn't smoke.
My smoking buddy would be my cousin but she don't smoke as much as me
#17: Is there someone in your life that you'd be proud to tell that you quit smoking? What do you think they would say? #smokingaffectsall
My mom. Both of my parents are reformed smokers, but my daddy works around it everyday, so the smell doesn't bother him as much. My mom hates it.
My daughter hopefully she'd be influenced to not smoke or quit if she already has started.
Have you ever tried to quit or reduce your smoking? Which strategy did you choose and how did it go? #TDII
Cold turkey. Quit four times like that, I just like smoking.
Hi John Green - thanks for sharing! What do you like about smoking?
Yes I have tried, i tried using music as a alternative.
Hi 10419 - cool! How did you do that and how did it work for you? Would you recommend it to someone who is trying to quit?

The way i went about it was when i would have the urge to smoke i would put my headphones in and play music. I honestly would have been successful in quitting however i live with other smokers and being around that caused me to grab another cigarette. Yes i would recommend this method for others trying to quit However i would also probably tell them that they may want to try to not be around other smokers untill they are fully comfortable and confident that they have successfully quit smoking. :)

These sound like very useful suggestions 10419 and I absolutely agree that being around other smokers can make it very hard. Would you try your music strategy again in a future attempt, should you ever be ready to try again?
Yes i would absolutely try this strategy for quitting again.
10419 and do you think you will ever be ready to try again?
I've got to run - see you next week. Bye!
I just like the act of smoking. Hookah, pot, tobacco, I enjoy it all.

#15: Most people who smoke report dealing with stress as their top reason for smoking. Work, class, family, friends, significant others -- it can be a lot! Can you think of another way to deal with stress that doesn’t involve lighting up when things get tough? What could you do instead? #balance
Well it's still smoking, but I would switch it from cigarettes to pot.
I like to go for walks when I'm stressed but I also smoke when I go. But exercise also does help and doesn't include smoking. Sex is an excellent stress reliever also lol
When I get too stressed, I lock myself in a room alone and get everything I need to do done.
I usually go walking around town or if really stressed go hiking and become one with nature
#14: How could you have a more active lifestyle without smoking? #balance
I'd be able to ride a bike without having an asthma attack. Run faster and further.
Doesn't effect me. To give you a look into how active my life is, I did a 20+ mile bike ride yesterday. Just to go eat. Didn't have to, I wanted to.
I already have an active lifestyle but my body would be healthier and the money I spend on squares I could use to go out and do other things
#13: Post your wish list here! #balance
I would use it to put towards my wedding.
Stuff for my daughter. More reptiles. A car. A place to call home
A brand new car!
Probably some weed.

data.caption: The Doctor Is In
data.description: Hi everyone, the next Q&A session will be on Wednesday. See you then!

data.message: #12: Yesterday we asked you to tell us how confident you were that you COULD quit smoking if you wanted to. What would it take to get you from the number you said yesterday to ONE NUMBER HIGHER? #motivation
I'd be more confident if i knew I had the support of my friends and family
I really don't know. It would be easier if I wasn't always around people who smoke.
#10: What is keeping quitting smoking from the top of your priorities list? What would make quitting even more important to you? #motivation
I don't quit because I still love smoking. I'll quit when I get pregnant.

I don't quit because I'm in the process of getting my life together and still going through some stressful stuff. The only thing that would cause me to quit sooner would be if my daughter started smoking young.
#9: On a scale of 1-10, how important is it to you to quit smoking for good? #motivation
Not really important to me at this time.
About a three. I still love smoking.
5 I mainly just want to cut back on how much I smoke
A 6 because I just want to cut back on my current smoking habits
It's really important I'm just not ready to commit to it yet
I agree with Cj, it's very important, just not really ready yet
What is currently your biggest smoking trigger? #TDII
My biggest trigger is stress
Hi 10430 - yeah that's definitely a big one for many people. What kind of situations tend to cause this stress for you?

Here recently it's mostly been my girlfriend. Even with my medicine she still ends up getting over my line and I get very violent thoughts. And they scare me because my medicine usually works pretty well in situations but with her it bypasses and the thoughts begin.
Yeah that does sound stressful and I can understand that you would be scared 10430. What else has worked for you in the past to stop or deal with these thoughts?
Marijuana and used to be really bad on bath salts until my daughter was born and i got my visitation.

Thanks for sharing 10430! I'm very impressed, sounds like you have actually already accomplished a lot for your family! This shows that you are quite capable of changing your behavior if you really want to. Have you ever tried other stress reduction techniques like deep breathing and relaxation for example?
Deep breathing I have tried but it didn't work
What else could you do in a stressful situation? Have you ever tried to exercise? If you ever wanted to give the relaxation another shot here is what you could try:
Sorry, I have to run. See you next week!
Stress is the only one that made me crave a cigarette. I don't normally feel the draw to smoke.
#8: Do you think you will ever want to quit smoking? If yes, when? #motivation
Yeah, in the future when I have no need to smoke tobacco normally.
Yes but I'm not sure exactly when
Eventually maybe. I know I'm going to want to at least for 6 weeks for a surgery but then I'll probably take it up again lol
I'll stop smoking when I get pregnant. Whether I pick it up again after the baby or not depends on how I feel after nine months without it.
Yea but not sure when

data.caption: The Doctor Is In
data.description: Hi everyone, the next Q&A session will be on Wednesday. See you!

data.message: #4: What was your reason for picking up that first cigarette? Was it to be cool, to be independent, to experiment, to look older, or something else? #beingconscious
To relieve stress and to get a break at work. Started smoking cigarettes at age 16.
I would say to fit in and look cool all my friends were
I was just barely 13 and at my friend's house while her mom was at work. Her mom rolled her own and so we decided to see what it was about. We've both been smoking since.
When I first started it was cause I thought that's what adults did. When I restarted it was for stress relief and to fit in with my friends
I first tried just to see what it was all about because both of my parents smoked, also thought it was the cool thing to do, regret that choice now.
Thank you for sharing this with us.
#5: What would be the best-case scenario if you quit smoking? #motivation
I wouldn't gain a ton of weight like I have in the past when I tried to quit, and my fiance and I could put that much more money toward our wedding at the end of the month.
Save money. Be healthier.
Better health, better influence on my daughter, save money
Set better examples for my kids, save money and not get cancer
#3: How would you support someone who tells you they want to quit smoking? #motivation
Tell them that it's simple if you put your mind to it. Any habit can be broken by replacing it with another 21 times in a row, just try to make it a healthier habbit.
Be supportive and not smoke around them
Not smoke around them and give them guidance.
Not smoke around them, tell them to wash all of their clothes and Febreeze the house if they smoke at home and try to go cold turkey.
Refrain from smoking around them when they aren't smoking. I wouldn't advise to quit cold turkey but to slowly bring their use down.

Welcome to the Tobacco Status Project! Thank you for joining us. We will start posting TODAY at 12 noon PDT! Here's how it works:1) We will share one post everyday for 90 days. Remember to turn on your notifications and check this page daily!2) You will receive $1 for each comment you share within 24 hours of each post. At the end of the 90-day program, we'll tally up all your comments and send you a gift card.3) Dr. Johannes Thrul will be joining us for 1 hour each week, during which he will answer any tobacco-related questions, share info and resources, and provide support to our group. Stay tuned for his first session TODAY!
What is the max of comments and $ a day?
The most you can earn each day is $1, but you're welcome to comment as much as you like! :)-Shirley from TSP
Ok thanks
Hi everyone and welcome to TSP! I am available for the next hour. Let me know if you have any questions! #TDII
What do you guys like about smoking?
It's a good stress reliever
It is a good stress reliever and it helps Me sleep
Also helps with my digestion after eating
#2: What are some of your favorite qualities about yourself?  How does smoking fit (or not fit) with that image of you? #balance
I guess my best quality would be I'm a good father. Everything I do is for my daughter. And i know smoking for one allows people to judge me as a bad father and 2 can influence her to smoke.

I'm blessed with enough strength to overcome an addiction to a extremely addictive substance...and now that I'm clean I'm tired of putting toxins in my body but cigarettes have been the hardest habit to break because they're legal and in every store.

Hello TSP members! We want you to know that this secret group is a great place to share your thoughts and engage in conversation. Please feel free to like or respond to each others' comments and share any relevant content of your own.To begin, let's take a moment to get to know each other a little better. Feel free to share with us:• Where you come from• Anything about your smoking (how much, how often, when you first started, etc.)• What you hope to gain from participating in the Tobacco Study ProjectThank you! We hope you're as excited as we are!

My name is 10430 I started smoking when I was 6 up to the age of 13. Then i had quit until I started back at 16. Now I'm up to a pack and a half a day. I'm hoping this study will help me at least cut back on how much i smoke.
#1: Share a success that you have had in the past. It can be anything from any time. Why did it work? Who helped you? #motivation
One of my greatest achievements was getting my scholarship to UMD three years ago. It worked because I work my butt off everyday for it. My parents helped and still help me with my college stuff.

Idk if you would consider it a success but here's my story. I moved a few states away from home when I was 14, my parents were trying to get better jobs. 7 years went by and we never went home once to see our family. Then last year my biological father invited me and my brother to come to Colorado with him and we did. After about 6 months there, me and my brother decided to go home(Indiana). I really good friend of ours drove all the way out there and picked us up. Needless to say, seeing my family again for the first time in 8 years(I'm 22 now) was probably one of the best feelings a person could experience, unexplainable. I would have to thank my biological father for this because I was scared of change and he gave me the courage to take a chance at change,ands now because ofthatt, I am finally back home with all my family, right where I belong!
A success of mine was getting visitation with my daughter. Her birth helped me get off bath salts and the weekly visits with her (I'm trying for more) gives me something to look forward to.
When you buy a pack with nothing but quarters
the struggle is real!
Only on my 3rd cigarette today. Woohoo
Smoking is expensive but it keeps me from being a psycho b****. Lol sorry, #truthfact
Same here. If I don't smoke all Hell breaks loose
Amen to that lol there have been times my very anti smoking gf has gone out, bought a pack, and thrown it at me lol
I just got back from a weekend trip up north and I smoked two and a half packs in two and a half days. I'm hoping to go back to my normal amount now that I'm home.
Ugh. Smokeless day.
I've done pretty good today. I've only smoked 5 ciggs. Granted I slept almost all day
Can't afford smokes today. This sucks.
I've only been awake for 3.5 hours and already on my 5th cigg
First day in months with no morning cigarette. Still truckin'

At twenty, I had been smoking for seven years and I was up to a pack a day, some days more. Now at almost twenty one I've managed to cut my smoking and make a pack last for three or four days! So much more manageable.
I remember back when I first started smoking, it was about 1.5 packs per day. 3 years later, Im down to about 6 cigarettesper day. Huge improvement.
Cigarettes take all of my money.

This group is for 18-25 year olds who smoke that want to learn more information about tobacco, how it affects your body, and the different quitting options available. Once you get more information about smoking and connect with other young adults who are in the same boat, you can decide if you want to make a change. Getting educated is the first step to making the right decision for YOU.
